          "body": "Verses 3-4 interrupt the psalm's God-ward movement with a sharp turn toward the adversaries. The interruption is deliberate — David looks at the threat directly before re-anchoring in the refrain of verse 5. What he sees is specific: these are not open enemies but hypocritical ones. They assault with intent to murder (62:3), counsel to thrust him from his position (62:4), and 'delight in falsehood' — *kazav*, a word meaning lie, a thing that deceives. Their distinguishing feature is the gap between mouth and inward life: they bless with their mouths while inwardly cursing. This is precisely the form of attack that a rock-and-stronghold metaphor answers. Physical force can be met with physical shelter; hypocrisy and slander can only be met by an authority higher than the social consensus the slanderers are manipulating. David cannot defend his reputation against those who speak well of him publicly while conspiring against him privately. He can only stand on the rock whose verdict does not depend on public speech. The New Testament development of this theme is direct: Jesus pronounces a woe on those whose 'hearts are far from' Him while their lips honor Him (Matthew 15:8, quoting Isaiah 29:13), and James identifies the double-tongued person as fundamentally unstable (James 3:9-12)."
