        "excerpt": "Trust in Him at all times, O people; pour out your heart before Him; God is a refuge for us.",
        "body": "Verse 8 marks the most significant structural pivot in the psalm: the movement from first-person singular to second-person plural. 'My soul... my rock... my salvation... my stronghold... my refuge' (62:1-7) becomes 'O people... before Him... a refuge for us.' David does not keep his theology of the rock as private property. His own experience of God as shelter grounds a communal imperative.\n\nThe command 'trust in Him at all times' uses *batach* — the primary Old Testament word for relational confidence, the act of leaning one's weight on something. The adverb is absolute: *at all times* (*bekhol-et*), not only in crisis, not only when circumstances make trust easy. The same word will appear in verse 10 in its prohibited form: 'do not trust in oppression.' *Batach* is the psalm's weight-transfer word — where does your soul place its load? — and the psalm names exactly two valid answers: God (62:8) and nothing else (62:10).\n\nThe command to 'pour out your heart before Him' (*shiphku* *levav*) is the psalm's most intimate instruction. The verb *shaphakh* is used elsewhere for pouring out water, blood, and strong emotion (Lamentations 2:12, 19; Psalm 79:6). To pour out the heart is to hold nothing back — no curated version of yourself, no presenting of needs selectively edited for divine approval, but the whole disordered interior laid before God. This is not a prayer technique; it is the natural consequence of having discovered that God is *refuge*. You pour out everything before the One whose shelter is not conditional on your presentation of yourself. The psalm's theology of trust and the psalm's theology of prayer are inseparable.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Batach* (trust, vv.8, 10) is the weight-bearing word; the noun *mibtach* (what one trusts in) appears as a synonym elsewhere. *Shaphakh levav* (pour out the heart) — shaphakh connotes pouring to emptiness, not a measured portion. *Machaseh* (refuge, vv.7, 8) — note that David's private 'my refuge' immediately becomes communal 'our refuge'; the shelter he has found is not private property."
